{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502657"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:48:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:48:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1884"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1884","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1884"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.12,0.2,0.18,0.35]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1884"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92384"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1884","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1884"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1884"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75689"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2924"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31547"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31548"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92384","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92384"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 42-year-old woman presents with a 12 hour history of constant pain in her right flank and associated persistent nausea and vomiting. She has no other symptoms. On examination her blood pressure is 110/60 mmHg, pulse 100/min and temperature 38.1\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft. Urinary dipstick shows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERed blood cells +++\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELeukocytes ++\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENitrites - negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProtein +\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer urine is then sent for microscopy, culture and sensitivity which is pending. A non-contrast CT scan of her abdomen and pelvis is arranged (Image)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence empiric oral antibiotics until cultures available","Percutaneous nephrolithotomy","Intravenous antibiotics and delay surgery until fevers settle","Ureteroscopic laser lithotripsy","Ureteric stent insertion"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has an obstructed and infected right kidney. She will require immediate hospital admission and intravenous antibiotics.However decompression of the obstructed kidney must not be delayed and the patient requires prompt passage of a \u003Cstrong\u003Eureteric stent - \u003C/strong\u003Eeven whilst she still has a fever. The stone is lodged in the upper ureter and would not be easily accessed by percutaneous nephrolithotomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf there was no clinical concern of infection, then a ureteroscopic laser lithotripsy could be attempted. If the ureter proved too tight to reach the stone, then a stent could be passed and the ureteroscopy re-attempted after an interval to allow the ureter to dilate sufficiently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAttempting ureteroscopy in the present circumstances could precipitate overwhelming urosepsis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe lack of nitrites on dipstick testing does not rule out the presence of infection. Nitrites may be positive in the presence of bacteria capable of elaborating the enzyme nitrate reductase, which converts urinary nitrates to nitrites. Many Gram negative organisms produce this enzyme but there are many urinary pathogens which do not, including Staphylococci and Enterococci. False negatives may also occur in the setting of a low colony-forming unit count (i.e. low bacterial load), recent void, or dilute urine.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["An acute obstructed renal tract with superimposed infection demands rapid decompression."],"references":["Turk C, Petrik A, Sarica K, Seitz C, Skolarikos A, Straub M, et al. EAU Guidelines on Interventional Treatment for Urolithiasis. Eur Urol. 2016;69(3):475-82.","Arumuham V, Byroft J. The Management of Urolithiasis. Surgery. 2016;34(7):352-360"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75689"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1884"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14545"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14545"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3ba9369c-e4bc-4931-8ec2-193025d62372.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3ba9369c-e4bc-4931-8ec2-193025d62372.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":497,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75689"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-17T14:56:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-17T14:56:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1884"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92384"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name